Lab 5: Wide and Deep Networks¶

Group Members: Eric Houtman, Rick Lattin, Kellen Long¶

In this lab, we explored the successfulness of video games in this dataset. It contains 16,598 video games with sales greater than 100,000 copies. The dataset contains 16 columns, including the name, platform, genre, publisher, developer, critic score, user score, total sales, and more. We will use this dataset to predict the total sales of a video game based on its other features.

For calculating the algorithm's performance, we used the f-1 score as well as the accuracy to adequately measure both the accuracy and precision of the predictions made by our model. For the dataset, the output value is the success of the game, which, using accuracy as a metric is not a bad idea. That is because the output is binary (did it sell more than 2 million copies globally or not). In the case of the f-1 score, it is a comprehensive metric that takes into account the false positives and false negatives, being the harmonic mean of precision and recall.

For dividing our data into training and testing, we used stratified k fold with 10 folds. We felt this would give us accurate splitting and segmentation of data by reducing the bias sampling by making sure that each fold is representative and effectivley dealing with any imbalances that were present in our dataset.

cross_columns = [['Platform', 'Genre']]
cross_columns2 = [['Developer', 'Publisher']]
cross_columns3 = [['Platform', 'Publisher'], ['Platform', 'Developer'], ['Platform', 'Genre']]

# cross each set of columns in the list above
cross_col_df_names1 = []
cross_col_df_names2 = []
cross_col_df_names3 = []
def fill_cross_columns(cross_columns):
    cross_col_df_names = []
    for cols_list in cross_columns:
        # encode as ints for the embedding
        enc = LabelEncoder()
        
        # 1. create crossed labels by join operation
        X_crossed_train = df_imputed[cols_list].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)
        
        # get a nice name for this new crossed column
        cross_col_name = '_'.join(cols_list)
        
        # 2. encode as integers
        enc.fit(np.hstack((X_crossed_train.to_numpy())))
        
        # 3. Save into dataframe with new name
        df_imputed[cross_col_name] = enc.transform(X_crossed_train)
        
        # keep track of the new names of the crossed columns
        cross_col_df_names.append(cross_col_name) 

    return cross_col_df_names

cross_col_df_names1 = fill_cross_columns(cross_columns)
cross_col_df_names2 = fill_cross_columns(cross_columns2)
cross_col_df_names3 = fill_cross_columns(cross_columns3)

First model¶

In [170]:
# we need to create separate lists for each branch
crossed_outputs = []

# CROSSED DATA INPUT
input_crossed = Input(shape=(X_train_cross.shape[1],), dtype='int64', name='wide_inputs')
for idx,col in enumerate(cross_col_df_names1):
    
    N = df_imputed[col].max()+1
    
    # this line of code does this: input_branch[:,idx]
    x = tf.gather(input_crossed, idx, axis=1)
    
    # now use an embedding to deal with integers as if they were one hot encoded
    x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                  output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                  input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(x)
    
    # save these outputs to concatenate later
    crossed_outputs.append(x)
    

# now concatenate the outputs and add a fully connected layer
wide_branch = concatenate(crossed_outputs, name='wide_concat')

# reset this input branch
all_deep_branch_outputs = []

# CATEGORICAL DATA INPUT
input_cat = Input(shape=(X_train_cat.shape[1],), dtype='int64', name='categorical_input')
for idx,col in enumerate(categorical_headers_ints):
    
    N = df_imputed[col].max()+1
    
    # this line of code does this: input_branch[:,idx]
    x = tf.gather(input_cat, idx, axis=1)
    
    # now use an embedding to deal with integers as if they were one hot encoded
    x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                  output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                  input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(x)
    
    # save these outputs to concatenate later
    all_deep_branch_outputs.append(x)
    
# NUMERIC DATA INPUT
# create dense input branch for numeric
input_num = Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],), name='numeric')
x_dense = Dense(units=20, activation='relu',name='num_1')(input_num)
    
all_deep_branch_outputs.append(x_dense)


# merge the deep branches together
deep_branch = concatenate(all_deep_branch_outputs,name='concat_embeds')
deep_branch = Dense(units=50,activation='relu', name='deep1')(deep_branch)
deep_branch = Dense(units=25,activation='relu', name='deep2')(deep_branch)
deep_branch = Dense(units=10,activation='relu', name='deep3')(deep_branch)
    
# merge the deep and wide branch
final_branch = concatenate([wide_branch, deep_branch],
                           name='concat_deep_wide')
final_branch = Dense(units=1,activation='sigmoid',
                     name='combined')(final_branch)

model = Model(inputs=[input_crossed,input_cat,input_num], 
              outputs=final_branch)

For our first model we are using the crossed column that is comprised of the platform and the genre of the video games to construct the wide layer of our network. We are using the standard three concatenated deep branches to represent the deep layers and are using the 'units' parameters of 50, 25 and 10 respectivley to control the depth of the network.

# we need to create separate lists for each branch
crossed_outputs = []

# CROSSED DATA INPUT
input_crossed = Input(shape=(X_train_cross.shape[1],), dtype='int64', name='wide_inputs')
for idx,col in enumerate(cross_col_df_names2):
    
    N = df_imputed[col].max()+1
    
    # this line of code does this: input_branch[:,idx]
    x = tf.gather(input_crossed, idx, axis=1)
    
    # now use an embedding to deal with integers as if they were one hot encoded
    x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                  output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                  input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(x)
    
    # save these outputs to concatenate later
    crossed_outputs.append(x)
    

# now concatenate the outputs and add a fully connected layer
wide_branch = concatenate(crossed_outputs, name='wide_concat')

# reset this input branch
all_deep_branch_outputs = []

# CATEGORICAL DATA INPUT
input_cat = Input(shape=(X_train_cat.shape[1],), dtype='int64', name='categorical_input')
for idx,col in enumerate(categorical_headers_ints):
    
    N = df_imputed[col].max()+1
    
    # this line of code does this: input_branch[:,idx]
    x = tf.gather(input_cat, idx, axis=1)
    
    # now use an embedding to deal with integers as if they were one hot encoded
    x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                  output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                  input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(x)
    
    # save these outputs to concatenate later
    all_deep_branch_outputs.append(x)
    
# NUMERIC DATA INPUT
# create dense input branch for numeric
input_num = Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],), name='numeric')
x_dense = Dense(units=20, activation='relu',name='num_1')(input_num)
    
all_deep_branch_outputs.append(x_dense)


# merge the deep branches together
deep_branch = concatenate(all_deep_branch_outputs,name='concat_embeds')
deep_branch = Dense(units=5,activation='relu', name='deep1')(deep_branch)
deep_branch = Dense(units=2,activation='relu', name='deep2')(deep_branch)
deep_branch = Dense(units=1,activation='relu', name='deep3')(deep_branch)

    
# merge the deep and wide branch
final_branch = concatenate([wide_branch, deep_branch],
                           name='concat_deep_wide')
final_branch = Dense(units=1,activation='sigmoid',
                     name='combined')(final_branch)

model2 = Model(inputs=[input_crossed,input_cat,input_num], 
              outputs=final_branch)

For our second model we are using the crossed column that is comprised of the developer and the publisher of the video games to construct the wide layer of our network. We are using the standard three concatenated deep branches to represent the deep layers and are using the 'units' parameters of 5, 2 and 1 respectivley to control the depth of the network.

# we need to create separate lists for each branch
crossed_outputs = []

# CROSSED DATA INPUT
input_crossed = Input(shape=(X_train_cross.shape[1],), dtype='int64', name='wide_inputs')
for idx,col in enumerate(cross_col_df_names1):
    
    N = df_imputed[col].max()+1
    
    # this line of code does this: input_branch[:,idx]
    x = tf.gather(input_crossed, idx, axis=1)
    
    # now use an embedding to deal with integers as if they were one hot encoded
    x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                  output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                  input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(x)
    
    # save these outputs to concatenate later
    crossed_outputs.append(x)
    

# now concatenate the outputs and add a fully connected layer
wide_branch = concatenate(crossed_outputs, name='wide_concat')

# reset this input branch
all_deep_branch_outputs = []

# CATEGORICAL DATA INPUT
input_cat = Input(shape=(X_train_cat.shape[1],), dtype='int64', name='categorical_input')
for idx,col in enumerate(categorical_headers_ints):
    
    N = df_imputed[col].max()+1
    
    # this line of code does this: input_branch[:,idx]
    x = tf.gather(input_cat, idx, axis=1)
    
    # now use an embedding to deal with integers as if they were one hot encoded
    x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                  output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                  input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(x)
    
    # save these outputs to concatenate later
    all_deep_branch_outputs.append(x)
    
# NUMERIC DATA INPUT
# create dense input branch for numeric
input_num = Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],), name='numeric')
x_dense = Dense(units=20, activation='relu',name='num_1')(input_num)
    
all_deep_branch_outputs.append(x_dense)


# merge the deep branches together
deep_branch = concatenate(all_deep_branch_outputs,name='concat_embeds')
deep_branch = Dense(units=1,activation='relu', name='deep1')(deep_branch)
    
# merge the deep and wide branch
final_branch = concatenate([wide_branch, deep_branch],
                           name='concat_deep_wide')
final_branch = Dense(units=1,activation='sigmoid',
                     name='combined')(final_branch)

model4 = Model(inputs=[input_crossed,input_cat,input_num], 
              outputs=final_branch)

For our fourth model we are using the crossed column that is comprised of the developer and the publisher of the video games to construct the wide layer of our network, same as our first model. For our deep layer, we removed two of the dense layers that comprise the deep branches and assigned the remaining dense layer to have a 'units' paramater of 1.

The closest comparison to this model is model 1. The key difference between the accuracy increase in these two models is that model 5 has a significantly smaller increase in performance. This can easily be attributed to overtraining and confounding the data by adding extraneous factors or making it overprocess the inputs. This is a great example as to why more is not always better. In neural networks, it is important to accurately assess the resources needed for a given task and to allocate them appropriately, otherwise the data will end up like this one, less efficient than its less over-engineered counterpart.

After viewing our results, we found that our first model was the most accurate, based on its F1-score. We then decided to compare its performance and accuracy to a standard multi-layer perceptron, calculating the F1-score based on the multi-layer perceptron's predictions.

After our comparison, we found that our model had a slightly better F1-score than the multi-layer perceptron, and therefore we decided to use our model for our final predictions. That being said, the results gathered from the multi-layer perceptron were still very accurate, and we believe that either model could be used for the final predictions. The deep and wide network would still provide more accuracy, however requires more time and complexity in order to run and test results.

def get_feature_names_from_weights(weights, names):
    tmp_array = []
    for comp in weights:
        tmp_string = ''
        for fidx,f in enumerate(names):
            if fidx>0 and comp[fidx]>=0:
                tmp_string+='+'
            tmp_string += '%.2f*%s ' % (comp[fidx],f[:-5])
        tmp_array.append(tmp_string)
    return tmp_array
